* ===========================================================================
* MCC_DEMO.DTS
* A guided tour of normal DotTalk++ database operations against the freshly
* built sample data.
*
* Status:  READ-ONLY DEMO
* Safety:  REPORT_ONLY -- no writes, no mutations, no index changes
* Purpose: Prove the sample foundation works, and show the shape of ordinary
*          use. This is the script the documentation and HELP files point at.
* Inputs:  data\dbf\x64\*.dbf + data\indexes\x64\*.cdx  (mcc_build_x64.dts)
* Outputs: transcript only
* Mutation: NONE
* Gate:    none -- read-only
*
* ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
* THE SHAPE OF NORMAL USE
*
*     USE <table>
*     SET INDEX TO <table>        (CNX or CDX, chosen by flavor)
*     SET ORDER TO TAG <tag>
*
* After that, ordinary database operations are available.
*
* AREA DISCIPLINE. There are 256 zero-based work areas. Each holds one table
* plus its sidecars. Almost every other operation depends on knowing which
* area you are in:
*
*     SELECT STUDENTS      by name
*     SELECT 8             by number
*
* Knowing which AREA you are working in matters as much as knowing which
* RECORD you are changing.
*
*     WORKSPACE            with no arguments, a read-only report of open areas
*
* ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
* INDEX FLAVOR IS AUTOMATIC
*     x64 / v128  ->  CDX   (runtime tag mutation supported)
*     x32 / VFP   ->  CNX   (sorted index by tag; batch REINDEX only)
* USE attaches the right one. You do not have to ask for it.
*
*   DOTSCRIPT TRACE scripts\mcc\mcc_demo.dts OUT tmp\mcc_demo.log
* ===========================================================================

SET ECHO OFF

ECHO ========================================================
ECHO MCC DEMO -- normal database operations
ECHO Read-only. Nothing here mutates anything.
ECHO ========================================================

* --- Two directories minimum, before any work ------------------------------

WORKSPACE CLOSE
SET PATH DBF DBF/x64
SET PATH INDEXES INDEXES/x64
SET PATH LMDB LMDB/x64
ECHO [SETUP] DBF -> DBF/x64   INDEXES -> INDEXES/x64   LMDB -> LMDB/x64

* ===========================================================================
* 1. OPEN THE WHOLE SET AND LOOK AT IT
* ===========================================================================
* WORKSPACE opens every table in the DBF slot at once, attaching each table's
* index by name. WORKSPACE with no arguments then reports what is open.

ECHO ========================================================
ECHO 1. OPEN THE SET
ECHO ========================================================

WORKSPACE OPEN DBF
WORKSPACE

* ===========================================================================
* 2. THE THREE-LINE OPENING MOVE
* ===========================================================================

ECHO ========================================================
ECHO 2. USE / SET INDEX / SET ORDER
ECHO ========================================================

SELECT STUDENTS
USE STUDENTS
SET INDEX TO STUDENTS
SET ORDER TO TAG LNAME

SHOW TABLE
SHOW COLUMNS

* ===========================================================================
* 3. READ IN LOGICAL ORDER
* ===========================================================================
* SMARTLIST honours the active tag order. LIST does not -- it walks the table
* physically. When order is what you are testing, SMARTLIST is the command.

ECHO ========================================================
ECHO 3. SMARTLIST -- ascending by LNAME
ECHO ========================================================

TOP
SMARTLIST 10

ECHO ========================================================
ECHO 4. DESC -- reverse the order, same tag
ECHO ========================================================

DESC
TOP
SMARTLIST 10

ECHO ========================================================
ECHO 5. TOP -- back to the first record in ASCENDING order
ECHO ========================================================
* Bare "ASC" does not undo DESC -- it takes an argument, and the 2026-07-14 run
* proved it: "ASC expects 1 argument(s)." The runner reported the error and
* CONTINUED, so the table stayed DESCENDING and the DESC state leaked into the
* LIST FOR below. The output looked fine; the order was wrong.
*
* Re-issuing SET ORDER TO TAG restores ascending, which is the default.

SET ORDER TO TAG LNAME
TOP
SMARTLIST 5

* ===========================================================================
* 6. QUERY
* ===========================================================================

ECHO ========================================================
ECHO 6. LIST FOR -- a predicate over the table
ECHO ========================================================

LIST FOR LNAME = WHITE

* ===========================================================================
* 7. RELATIONS -- the point of the sample set
* ===========================================================================
* MCC is a relational fixture, not just twelve loose tables:
*
*     STUDENTS.SID     -> ENROLL.SID, STUD_MAJ.SID
*     STUDENTS.MAJOR   -> MAJORS.MAJOR
*     CLASSES.CLS_ID   -> ENROLL.CLS_ID, TASSIGN.CLS_ID
*     CLASSES.CID      -> COURSES.CID
*     COURSES.DEPT_ID  -> DEPT.DEPT_ID
*     ROOMS.BLDG       -> BUILDING.BLDG
*
* WORKSPACE SAVE persists the relations graph alongside the areas, which is
* why the workspace file is worth more than a list of filenames.

ECHO ========================================================
ECHO 7. ENROLL -- the child side, ordered by SID
ECHO ========================================================

SELECT ENROLL
SET INDEX TO ENROLL
SET ORDER TO TAG SID
TOP
SMARTLIST SID,CLS_ID NEXT 10

ECHO ========================================================
ECHO 8. AREA REPORT -- where am I?
ECHO ========================================================

WORKSPACE

ECHO ========================================================
ECHO DEMO COMPLETE. Nothing was mutated.
ECHO
ECHO ---------------------------------------------------------
ECHO DESTRUCTIVE OPERATIONS -- shown, NOT run.
ECHO
ECHO These change data. They are deliberately absent from this
ECHO read-only demo. Run them only against a disposable fixture,
ECHO never against the sample foundation -- every help file and
ECHO lesson downstream assumes this data is virgin.
ECHO
ECHO     REPLACE LNAME WITH GRIMWOOD
ECHO     CALC GPA = GPA + 1
ECHO
ECHO If you do mutate the sample data, restore it:
ECHO     .\dottalkpp\scripts\mcc\reset_mcc_fixtures.ps1 -Execute
ECHO     then re-run stages 1..3.
ECHO ---------------------------------------------------------
ECHO ========================================================
